  "output": "## Findings\n\nNo React/frontend exists in this repo — it's a pure Python job-scraper pipeline (async fetchers → SQLite store → notifiers). I've skipped the React section and focused the other four categories on real patterns found in the code.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `store.py:60-72` (`Store.diff`)\n\nFor every job in the batch, a separate `SELECT` is issued in a Python loop:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    ...\n```\n\nWith hundreds of jobs across all `sources.yaml` entries, that's hundreds of round-trips (SQLite is embedded so it's cheap per-call, but it's still O(N) `execute()` calls plus O(N) individual `INSERT`/`UPDATE` statements instead of batched ones — and it compounds with the parallel-worker DB contention noted in memory).\n\n**Fix — one batched SELECT + `executemany` for the writes:**\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    existing = {}\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    CHUNK = 500  # SQLite's default variable limit is 999\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), CHUNK):\n        chunk = keys[i:i + CHUNK]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update((r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in cur.execute(q, chunk))\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    inserts, updates = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev = existing.get(job.key)\n        row = {**job.to_row(), \"now\": now}\n        if prev is None:\n            new.append(job); inserts.append(row)\n        elif prev != row[\"content_hash\"]:\n            changed.append(job); updates.append(row)\n        else:\n            touched.append((now, job.key))\n\n    if inserts:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title,\n            url, location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n            content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n            VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n            :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n            inserts)\n    if updates:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n            salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now\n            WHERE key=:key\"\"\", updates)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", touched)\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\nTurns O(N) statements into O(N/500 + 3).\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — `filters.py:15-42` (`match`)\n\n`_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **recompile the same regex list on every single job** — `filter_jobs` calls `match()` once per job in its list comprehension (`filters.py:49`), so keyword patterns get re-compiled O(jobs × keywords) times instead of once.\n\n**Fix — compile once, pass compiled patterns down:**\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = None\n    if max_age := rules.get(\"max_age_days\"):\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in (rules.get(\"locations\") or [])]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job: Job, *, include=None, exclude=None, locations=None, cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    if locations and not any(l in job.location.lower() for l in locations):\n        return False\n    if cutoff is not None:\n        dt = job.posted_dt\n        if dt is not None and dt < cutoff:\n            return False\n    return True\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `models.py:66-75` (`Job.content_hash`)\n\n`content_hash` is a `@property` that re-runs SHA-256 every access. In `Store.diff` it's read once for comparison (`row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash`) and then again inside `to_row()` (called from `_insert`/`_update`) — two hashes per new/changed job. Cheap individually, but avoidable: compute once and reuse (the batched `diff` rewrite above already does this implicitly since `row[\"content_hash\"]` from `to_row()` is reused for both the dict comparison and the write).\n\n### 4. Memory growth — `models.py:52` (`Job.raw`)\n\nEvery `Job` carries the **full raw source payload** (`raw: dict = field(default_factory=dict)`), and it's never read again after parsing — `to_row()` explicitly pops it before persisting (`store.py`/`models.py:73`), and `filters.py`/`notify.py` never touch it. For boards that paginate hundreds of roles (Google, Eightfold, Amazon — up to 40 pages), the whole pipeline run holds every raw JSON blob in memory simultaneously for no downstream benefit.\n\n**Fix:** either don't populate `raw` in the parsers that don't need it for debugging, or drop it right after parsing:\n```python\njobs = [dataclasses.replace(j, raw={}) for j in jobs]   # after fetch_all(), before filter/store\n```\nNot a leak (process exits after each run), but unnecessary peak-memory overhead that scales with board size.\n\n### 5. Caching opportunity — HTTP fetches (`fetchers.py`)\n\nThe pipeline runs every 12h (per your scheduled-run setup) and **fully re-fetches and re-paginates every source** — including 20-40 page GETs for Google/Eightfold — with no conditional requests. `store.py` already has a generic `meta` k/v table (used for `last_scan` and `report_seq`); it's a natural place to cache an `ETag`/`Last-Modified` per source and send `If-None-Match`/`If-Modified-Since`, skipping full re-parse on a 304 for sources that support it. Lower priority since dedup already happens via `content_hash`, but it'd cut bandwidth/CPU on unchanged large boards.\n\n### 6. Minor — `notify.py` sequential blocking calls, no connection reuse\n\n`dispatch()` (`notify.py:105-109`) calls each notifier in sequence, and `notify_slack`/`notify_webhook`/`notify_sms` each do a bare `httpx.post(...)`, opening a fresh connection (TCP+TLS handshake) every call instead of reusing a pooled client. Low-impact today (dispatch runs once after all async work completes, so it's not blocking the event loop), but if you add more webhook-style notifiers this will add up:\n```python\n_client = httpx.Client(timeout=15)  # module-level, reused across all notifier calls\n...\ndef notify_slack(new, changed):\n    ...\n    _client.post(url, json={\"text\": text})\n```\n\n### Not applicable\n- **React re-renders**: no frontend in this repo.\n- **SQLite concurrency**: `Store.__init__` doesn't set `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL`, which is worth adding given the parallel-worker DB contention already noted in your memory (`jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions.md`) — pairs well with fix #1 since batching also shrinks the write-lock window.\n\nThe store.py N+1 fix and filters.py recompilation fix are the two with real, measurable impact; the rest are smaller wins. Want me to implement any of these?\n",
